{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626064"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17051"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17051"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.07,0.24,0.24,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9741"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5147"},{"type":"tags","id":"10075"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrsodeoxycholic acid is a naturally occurring bile acid that has important therapeutic applications in hepatobiliary disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Replaces hydrophobic bile acids with hydrophilic bile acids","Increases bile acid synthesis","Inhibits cholesterol synthesis","Increases bile acid secretion","Stimulates gallbladder contraction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of ursodeoxycholic acid involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ereplacing hydrophobic bile acids with hydrophilic bile acids\u003C/strong\u003E. This replacement reduces the overall toxicity of the bile acid pool and helps protect hepatocytes from damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen considering \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased bile acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E, ursodeoxycholic acid suppresses endogenous bile acid synthesis through negative feedback.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder contraction stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E, ursodeoxycholic acid does not significantly affect gallbladder motility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol synthesis inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary mechanism of action of UDCA. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn terms of \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased bile acid secretion\u003C/strong\u003E, the main effect is a qualitative change in bile composition rather than increased secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy making the bile acid pool more hydrophilic, ursodeoxycholic acid reduces cholesterol absorption and secretion, therefore treating cholestatic liver diseases and dissolving certain types of gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ursodeoxycholic acid is a hydrophilic bile acid that reduces cholesterol absorption and secretion.","Ursodeoxycholic acid decreases the toxicity of the bile acid pool by replacing more hydrophobic bile acids.","The main therapeutic use of ursodeoxycholic acid is in treating cholestatic liver diseases and gallstones."],"references":["Paumgartner G, Beuers U. Mechanisms of action and therapeutic efficacy of ursodeoxycholic acid in cholestatic liver disease. Clin Liver Dis. 2004;8(1):67-vi. doi:10.1016/S1089-3261(03)00135-1","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17051"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59461"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T08:38:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T08:27:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9741"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Rememb